Pybind11 seems to perform conversion between floating point and integer types.

    #include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
    #include <iostream>

    void MyFunction(int i) { std::cout << " integer: " << i << "\n"; }
    void MyFunction(double d) { std::cout << " double: " << d << "\n"; }

    PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
        pybind11::module m("example", "pybind example plugin");
        m.def("MyFunction", static_cast<void(*)(int)>(MyFunction));
        m.def("MyFunction", static_cast<void(*)(double)>(MyFunction));
        return m.ptr();
    }


For example, the integer version of MyFunction will truncate a python float, and the double version will expand a python int. When overloaded, the version of MyFunction called is always whichever was exported first.

This comes from cpython helpfully doing the conversion (ie, in `PyLong_AsLong`) rather than checking the type.

I would think floating point -> integer would be disallowed, since it would almost always truncate. The other direction is possibly ok, although there is risk of loss of precision with large integers (and overloads wouldn't work). The checks are pretty easy to insert, but I was curious of your thoughts of what should be allowed and what shouldn't.

